Introduction

This report provides an exploratory overview of snowshoe hare populations from 1998 - 2012 at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest in Alaska (Kielland, K.et al.(2017)). Specifically, the report evaluates snowshoe hare trap counts over 13 years. It also compares juvenile hare weights across males and females at three sites; Bonbs, Bonanza Mature, and Bonanza Riparian. Finally, the report analyzes a potentialrelationship between hind foot length (mm) and weights (g).

Data & Analysis

Snowshoe hare trap count, weight and hind foot length data were collected and made available by Senior Investigator Knut Kielland and colleagues at the Bonanza Creek (LTER) site in Alaska. Capture - recapture studies were conducted of snowshoe hares at 5 locales in the Tanana Valley. The data contain observations for 378 juvenile hares, collected over 13 years (1998 - 2012). Following exploratory data visualization, juvenile hare male and female weights are compared by two-sample t-tests using a significance level () f 0.05 throughout. Differences between the groups are described by Cohens d effect size. The relationship between weight and hind foot length is explored by a simple linear regression. All analyses are in R version 4.1.1 using R studio version 1.4.1717.

Preliminary Results

A. Juvenile Hare Trap Counts

Figure 1: Total Juvenile Hare Trap Count by Year Total juvenile hare trap counts per year from 1998 - 2012.

Juvenile Trap Count Analysis

There is a decrease in juvenile hare trap counts during the time period 1998 - 2012. The minimum count of juvenile hare trap counts reported was 2 in 2012. The maximum count reported was 126 in 1999. The overall mean of juvenile hare trap counts was 31.5 and the median was 18.5. The standard deviation was reported at 35.9 hares traped.

To standardize the juvenile hare population in future analyses, the number of days and traps in the study need to be consistent every year.

Juvenile Weight Analysis

The graph shows a visual difference in counts for juvenile hare weights for both males and females. Bonanza Riparian has the highest sample size of juvenile hares at 242. This is followed by Bonanza Mature with a sample size of 82 and Bonbs at 47. The central tendency for females is generally lower than the central tendency of males. This is visualized by the black dots on the graph which represent mean values. The sample size impacts the visible trends and the accuracy of the data.

Juvenile Weight Comparison Analysis

On average, male juvenile hares weight more than female juveniles hares. The actual difference in mean weights between female and males is 90.5 (g), with a small effect size (Cohens d = -0.29). Further investigation would be needed to identify whether there is a significant difference between male and female weights despite statistical significance (t(325) = 2.7, p-value: 0.0071, n = 378).

D. Juvenile Weight & Hind Foot Length

Figure 3: Juvenile Weight and Hind Foot Length Comparison Relationship between Hind Foot Length (mm) and Weight (g) for juvenile snowshoe hares recorded from 1998 2012 at Bonanza Creek. Points indicate individual juvenile hare measurements.

Juvenile Weight and Hindfoot Analysis

The slope is 9.52 (g/mm). On average we expect weight to increase by 9.52 for every 1 mm increase in hind foot length. The y-intercept is -279.3 (g). For a juvenile hare with a 0 mm hind foot length, we expect an average hare mass of -279.3 (g).

The R^2 value of 0.3 means that 30% of the variance in hare weight is explained by hind foot length. The Pearsons r Correlation is 0.5. This value represents a moderate correlation between the change in weight and hind foot length.

Despite the regression line illustrating a positive correlation, the R^2 and Pearsons r values only support a moderate correlation between weight and hind foot length.

Summary

Exploratory data analysis reveals the following initial findings:

  • The total juvenile hare trap counts by year steadily declined from the beginning of sampling (1999) to the end (2012).
  • There is a statistically significant difference in means between male and female juvenile snowshoe hare weights, however the effect size is small.
  • The lack of homoscedasticity in the relationship between hare weight
    1. and hind foot length (mm) suggest that the regression model may need to include additional predictor variables to explain the performance of the dependent variable.

Next Steps:

  • Multiple linear regression to understand the relationship between sex, hind foot length and weight
